<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-perp_parallel" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Parallel and Perpendicular Lines</title>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
	Determine whether two lines are parallel, perpendicular, or neither.
      </li>
      <li>
	Find the equation of a line parallel to a given line.
      </li>
      <li>
	Find the equation of a line perpendicular to a given line.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <definition xml:id="def-parallel">
    <title>Parallel</title>
    <p>
      Two lines in the Cartesian plane are said to be <term>parallel</term>
      <idx>
	<h>Line</h>
	<h>Parallel</h>
      </idx>
      if they do not intersect.
    </p>
  </definition>

  <figure xml:id="fig-parallel_lines">
    <image xml:id="img-parallel_lines">
      <latex-image>
	<xi:include parse="text" href="tex/parallel.tex"/>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <caption>Parallel lines.</caption>
  </figure>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-parallel">
    <statement>
      Two lines are parallel if and only if they have the same slope.
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Determine whether the lines
	<me>
	  -x + 3y=-4
	  \quad\text{and}\quad
	  -4x + 12y = 9
	</me>
	are parallel.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
	In order to determine whether these lines are parallel, we need to find the slope of each line.
	We do this by placing each line into <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="title"/>.
      </p>
      <p>
	For the first line, add <m>x</m> to both sides
	<me>3y = x - 4</me>
	and divide both sides by <m>3</m>
	<me>y = \frac{1}{3} - \frac{4}{3}.</me>
	This tells us the slope of the line <m>-x + 3y = -4</m> is <m>1/3</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
	For the second line, add <m>4x</m> to both sides
	<me>12y = 4x + 9,</me>
	divide both sides by <m>12</m>
	<me>y = \frac{4}{12}x + \frac{9}{12}</me>
	and reduce
	<me>y = \frac{1}{3}x + \frac{3}{4}.</me>
	This tells the slope of the line <m>-4x + 12y = 9</m> is also <m>1/3</m>.
	Therefore the lines <m>-x + 3y = -4</m> and <m>-4x + 12y = 9</m> are parallel by <xref ref="thm-parallel"/>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Find the equation of the line parallel to <m>4x + 2y = 9</m> that passes through the point <m>(-1,5)</m>.
	Write your answer in <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="title"/>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	First, find the slope of the line <m>4x + 2y = 9</m> by placing the equation into <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="title"/>.
	Subtract <m>4x</m> from both sides
	<me>2y = -4x + 9,</me>
	divide both sides by <m>2</m>
	<me>y = -\frac{4}{2}x + \frac{9}{2}</me>
	and simplify to
	<me>y = -2x + \frac{9}{2}.</me>
	In this form, we see the slope of the line is <m>-2.</m>
      </p>
      <p>
	By <xref ref="thm-parallel"/>, the slope of a line parallel to <m>4x + 2y = 9</m> is <m>-2</m>.
	Now we use <xref ref="thm-point_slope"/> to write down a line with slope <m>-2</m> through the point <m>(-1,5)</m>
	<me>y - 5 = -2(x - (-1))</me>
	and simplify
	<me>y - 5 = -2(x + 1).</me>
      </p>
      <p>
	Finally, to put this line into <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="title"/>, distribute the <m>-2</m>
	<me>y - 5 = -2x - 2,</me>
	add 5 to both sides of the equation
	<me>y = -2x -2 + 5,</me>
	and simplify
	<me>y = -2x + 3.</me>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <definition xml:id="def-perpendicular">
    <p>
      Two lines are <term>perpendicular</term>
      <idx>
	<h>Line</h>
	<h>Perpendicular</h>
      </idx>
      if they intersect at a right angle.
    </p>
  </definition>
  
  <figure xml:id="fig-perpendicular_lines">
    <image xml:id="img-perpendicular_lines">
      <latex-image>
	<xi:include parse="text" href="tex/perpendicular.tex"/>
      </latex-image>
    </image>
    <caption>Perpendicular lines.</caption>
  </figure>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-perpendicular">
    <statement>
      <p>
	Two lines are perpendicular if and only if the product of their slopes is <m>-1</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Determine whether the lines
      <me>3x + 5y = 7
      \quad\text{and}\quad
      -5x + 3y = 21
      </me>
      are perpendicular.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	First we must place the lines in <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="title"/> to find the slopes.
	The first equation becomes
	<md>
	  <mrow>3x + 5y \amp= 7 \amp \amp \text{Subtract}\ 3x\ \text{from both sides}</mrow>
	  <mrow>5y \amp= -3x + 7 \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ 5</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp= \frac{-3x + 7}{5} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = -\frac{3}{5}x + \frac{7}{5}.</mrow>
	</md>
	In this form, we can read off the slope of the line as <m>-3/5.</m>
      </p>
      <p>
	The second equation becomes
	<md>
	  <mrow> -5x + 3y \amp = 21 \amp\amp \text{Add}\ 5x\ \text{to both sides}</mrow>
	  <mrow>3y \amp= 5x + 21 \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ 3</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = \frac{5x + 21}{3} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = \frac{5}{3}x + 7.</mrow>
	</md>
	In this form, we can read off the slop of the line as <m>5/3</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
	Finally, to check whether these lines are parallel, we compute the product of these slopes.
	Since
	<me>-\frac{3}{5} \times \frac{5}{3} = -\frac{15}{15} = -1</me>
	we conclude that these lines are perpendicular by <xref ref="thm-perpendicular"/>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
	Find the equation of a line perpendicular to <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> that passes through the point <m>(3,5)</m>.
	Write your answer in <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="title"/> form.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
	First, place the line in <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="title"/>
	<md>
	  <mrow>2x + 3y \amp= 5 \amp\amp \text{Subtract}\ 2x\ \text{from both sides}</mrow>
	  <mrow>3y \amp = -2x + 5 \amp\amp \text{Divide both sides by}\ 3</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = \frac{-2x + 5}{3} \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = -\frac{2}{3}x + \frac{5}{3}.</mrow>
	</md>
	We can read off the slope as <m>-2/3</m> from this equation.
      </p>
      <p>
	To find the slope, <m>m</m>, of a perpendicular line, <xref ref="thm-perpendicular"/> tells us we must solve the equation
	<me>-\frac{2}{3} m = -1</me>
	for <m>m</m>:
	<md>
	  <mrow>-\frac{2}{3} m \amp= -1 \amp\amp \text{Multiply both sides by}\ -\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
	  <mrow>-\frac{3}{2}\left(-\frac{2}{3}m\right) \amp = -\frac{3}{2}\left(-1\right) \amp\amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>m \amp = \frac{3}{2}.</mrow>
	</md>
      </p>
      <p>
	Using <xref ref="thm-point_slope" text="title"/>, the equation of the line perpendicular to <m>2x + 3y = 5</m> that passes through the point <m>(3,5)</m> is
	<me>y - 5 = \frac{3}{2}(x - 3).</me>
	Finally, we convert to <xref ref="thm-slope_intercept" text="title"/>
	<md>
	  <mrow>y - 5 \amp= \frac{3}{2}(x - 3) \amp \amp \text{Distribute}</mrow>
	  <mrow>y - 5 \amp = \frac{3}{2}x - \frac{9}{2} \amp\amp \text{Add}\ 5\ \text{to both sides}</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = \frac{3}{2}x - \frac{9}{2} + 5 \amp\amp \text{Find a common denominator}</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = \frac{3}{2} x - \frac{9}{2} + \frac{10}{2} \amp \amp \text{Simplify}</mrow>
	  <mrow>y \amp = \frac{3}{2}x + \frac{1}{2}.</mrow>
	</md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
